 and the Aesthetics of Ecstatic Naturalism -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough there are distinctly American artists—Walt Whitman, Herman Melville, Grandma Moses, Thomas Hart Benton, and Andy Warhol, for example—very little attention has been devoted to formulating any distinctively American characteristics of aesthetic judgment and practice. This volume takes a step in this direction, presenting an introductory essay on the possibility of such a distinctly American tradition, and a collection of essays exploring particular examples from a variety of angles. Some of the essays in this collection extend pragmatist and process insights about the important place aesthetics has in molding and assessing experience. Other essays examine the place of American aesthetics in relation to such particular forms of art as painting, literature, music, and film. Three essays attend to the aesthetic aspects of a flourishing life. In each of the essays, American aesthetics is understood to arise out of deeply felt personal, historical, and cultural backgrounds. Consequently, not only are such relatively abstract notions as harmony, fit, elegance, proportion, and the like involved in aesthetic judgment, but also religious, political, and social factors become embroiled in aesthetic discernment. Thus the ongoing pattern of American aesthetics is shown to be distinguishable from such other varieties of aesthetic thought as analytic aesthetics, New Criticism, and postmodern approaches to aesthetics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAesthetics, American. 4aPhilosophy : Aesthetics. 4aPhilosophy : American Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Pragmatism. 4aPhilosophy : Process Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Aesthetics.2bisacsh1 aAuxier, Randall E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorrington, Robert S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrieth, Corey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaskill, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilbertson, Leanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodson, Jacob L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGulick, Walter B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGulick, Walter B., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGulick, Walter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHart, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aInnis, Robert E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeddy, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcLachlan, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcternan, Vaughan Durkee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNeville, Robert Cummings, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRaposa, Michael L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRohr, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosenberg, Harold, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShusterman, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSlater, Gary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSlater, Gary, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStewart, Arthur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStrong, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWildman